Java Script



Diference between const and let:
const declares a variable with a constant value.
 Meaning once you assign a value to a const variable, 
you cannot reasign it later in your code.

let declares a variable that can be reassigned later in your code.

- A string data type is a collection or sequence of characters treated 
as a single unit. 
lLStrings can include letters, numbers, symbols, and even spaces. 

Template literals are string literals that allow for embedded expressions.
 They are enclosed by the backtick (`) character instead of single or
  double quotes. Template literals can contain placeholders, which are 
  indicated by the dollar sign and curly braces (${expression}).

let name = 'Alicia';
let age = 25;
let message2 = `My name is ${name} and I am ${age} years old.`;

- index.html it's a common convention in web development to name the main
 entry point of a website or directory.
This convention originated from early web servers, which would automatically serve an "index.html" file when a directory was accessed without specifying a file name. 


-JavaScript is the "brain" behind the dynamic content on websites, allowing you to create things like skllideshows, forms and games.

-To create a JavaScript file, you semply need to create a text file and save it with a  .js extension. example script.js 

-----Basic Structure of a JavaScript File -----

// This is a comment - it won't be executed
// comments are for explaining your code

// Define a variable
let greeting = "Hello, world!;

  
// Funrion to display a greeting
function sayHello() {
  console.log(greeting);
}

// Call the function
sayHello();


-----How to link JavaScript to an HTML File----

-Use <script> to link JavaScript to file. Place tag inside the <head> or at the end of the <body> section of your HTML file.

example: In this expample the deffer attribute ensures the script runs after the HTML is fully parsed, which helps prevent issues when the script tries to access HTML elements that haven't been loaded yet.

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <neta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>My First JavaScript Project</title>
  <script src="script.js" defer></script> <!-- Lint to the JavaScript file -->
</head> 
<body>
  <h1>Welcome to my Website</h1>
</body>
</html>

To run your JavaScript code open HTML file (index.html) in a web browser. You can use browser developer tools( open F12) to see console output, where the console.log(greeting); statement will print "Hello, world!".

